annotations:
And there’s a millipede
 Angry on your carpet

As the relationship has gone on, the singer has become more and more sympathetic to her partner’s fears. Being engrossed in their anxieties has rubbed them off on her, at least somewhat, and she has begun to think similarly.
’Cause I must make you the perfect evening

This line slightly varies from the previous chorus, replacing the word “morning” with “evening.” This signals progression in the narrator’s life as well as their partner’s and implies that the issues the narrator’s partner deals with are chronic.

Oh, and I digress
 ’Cause I must make you the perfect morning
 And I try my best
 To prove that nothing’s out to get you
 To prove that nothing’s out to get you

The final line is the culmination of the work– ending on the potent note that the narrator wants her partner not only to feel safe, but to be able to appreciate the world with her, both the good and the bad, the serene and the tumultuous, the myriad beautiful forms of life that scurry the walls of their home.

The title “The Bug Collector” drives this point home. It reveals that the narrator finds beauty in all the things her partner fears, and that an alleviation of that fear is not a replacement for a true change in perspective– an ability to see beauty in the ugly.

Oh, and I must admit
 He’s staring with a vengeance

The narrator admits that she, too, understands her partner’s worries. She recognizes the ill intent of the world, the immense destructive strength that negative forces can have in an otherwise safe relationship (as illustrated by the bugs in the house).

I try my best
 To put the priest inside a jam jar

This recontexualizes the fear of the narrator’s partner– as if the narrator knows her partner’s anxieties about the world are preventing them from fully experiencing that world, from recognizing the holiness that lies in the struggle of the everyday.

And there’s a praying mantis
 Prancing on your bathtub
 And you swear it’s a priest
 From a past life out to getcha

The “priest” the narrator’s partner sees in the mantis elevates their fear beyond general anxiety or fear of the unpleasant (bugs in the house). It seems to imply a religious significance, to imply that the praying mantis is some holy symbol, perhaps a representation of the beauty that hardships and negative influences can ultimately have on a life.

I try my best
 To scoop the slugger out the window
The narrator removes this negative force from their home. The word “slugger” here seems to imply a certain indifference to this act, though this disposition changes as the song progresses.

And I digress
 ’Cause I must make you the perfect morning
The narrator wants to absolve her partner of this fear– by protecting them and isolating them from the anxiety they have about the world.

And there’s a centipede
 Naked in your bedroom
 Oh, and you swear to God
 The fucker’s out to get you

“The Bug Collector” details a relationship plagued by fear. The centipede is “naked” in the bedroom, implying a kind of defenselessness or purity to the animal, but the narrator’s partner is convinced that it is full of concentrated malice.

annotations:
’Cause making this song up is just as hard
 ’Cause making this song up is just as hard
This line shows how simple it can be to start cleaning ones mind from anxiety and self-doubt, so easy that even self realizing your mistakes and anxiety is just as hard.

I’m throwing out the milk
 The olives got old
 I’m tired of my mind getting heavy with mold

After a long period of anxiety and confusion, the singer has finally realized that she needs to let go of what’s been weighing her down and focus instead on caring for herself and finding personal meaning.
Arbitrary sonogram

Arbitrary is defined as something that is based on chance with no reason or significance (in my own words)

A Sonogram is “a visual image produced from an ultrasound examination”. Connotatively this is referring to the first time a parent will see tangible evidence of their future child.

Figuratively this is an interesting juxtaposition, something meaningless that is generally considered very accurate and significant.
The milk is sour
the milk is sour could state that the time has run out, it’s already to late to drink it cause it has expired.

the milk is sour could state that the time has run out, it’s already to late to drink it cause it has expired.
She’ll never get to eat you like your heart’s a pomegranate

Though delicious, pomegranates are notoriously time-consuming to eat, so the idea of one’s heart being likened to one suggests a complexity and substantial investment of time and effort– and a substantial reward, accordingly- on the part of one’s lover.

I need to start a garden
 I need to start a garden
 I need to start a garden
 I need to start a garden!

The garden, in this song, serves as a metaphor of mental purity. Up to here, the verses have explored stagnation. The narrator has been struggling with self-doubt and anxiety, and has hiding from the world to maintain stability.

But this verse is the catharsis. The narrator decides that they have to overcome their anxiety and pursue experiences. They’re tossing the milk and dusting off their mind, and they’re going outside to start a garden – to start over.

The garden metaphor works especially well because a garden needs to be tended regularly. Starting a garden requires committing oneself to something,  which the narrator does here.

Courtney Barnett uses the “gardening” metaphor similarly in her song “Avant Gardener.”,

annotations:
I am letting you go
 I am letting you go
 I am letting you go awry

She seems to be telling this person that they are free to leave her; she won’t hold them back. But with the addition of “awry” in the third line, the meaning could change to her allowing their irregular or chaotic behavior to go on.

It was more than a race
 More than the wind
 Chasing the flood
 You opened the gate
 
 And fate is a sundress
 Ripped at the thigh
 Thigh high and safety net
 Swarmed by the hornets’ nest
 To cover my eyes
 
 It was more a mirage
 In sickness and health
 I showed you a body
 Like a cluttered garage

I always felt these lines had to do with her body image. The ‘fight, flight or freeze’ response that kicks in with the perceived danger of revealing herself shows in the first verse as a triple construction. It serves as a way to explain the pace of her quickly the fear takes hold, as well as using the metaphor of a flood to show the devastation about to ensue. In the second verse, her ‘covering her eyes’ also indicates a freeze response.

 What gives credence to this being about body image is the imagery in the second and third verses.  “I showed you a body like a cluttered garage” especially resonates with the guilt, embarrassment, and how often she opens up the rest of her body to others. Plot wise in the second verse, it follows her sundress being torn and underneath there still being protection with her ‘safety’ net stockings. The pain felt here is related to an entomophobic fear of hornets and hornets covering her body.

the final reason this could be tied to body image specifically rather than sexual assault or something is in the first two lines of the third verse. It details perception as a mirage rather than a concrete event.  Further, the perception of her body is said to be felt in sickness and health, leaning towards the idea that it is a long term mental problem.

I like this song for the detail it manages to pack in within a small use of words (mostly in reference to the second verse here) and how well she invokes the feelings of dealing of body image issues without overstating them either.

body.plain: Heynderickx said it was about “the divine feminine” when she opened for Lucy Dacus on November 9th, 2022, at the Moore Theater.

annotations:
Oh my web is still spinning
 My web is still spinning

Who’s doing the spinning here changes– At first it seems as if the singer’s god is in control of the singer, but then Hendrickx refers to her web. This could be because Hendrickx is describing a fantasy of her own that has leaked into her real life. This image of a lover that she’s created has begun driving her, but it is ultimately something that is difficult to bring about on one’s own terms– hence the line “You can’t see it yet.” The singer is still spinning her web, she is still working towards this ideal. The chorus depicts a reverse of how we tend to think about what goes on in our heads. Instead of us being in control of our ideas, Hendrickx shows how our thoughts and fantasies can become our gods.

Or maybe my god
 Has thick hips and big lips

The religious themes come through here, with Hendrickx including the detail that her hypothetical lover does not appeal to traditional Eurocentric beauty standards. She rejects the notion that European features, as depicted in many religious artworks, are any closer to godliness than that of other ancestries.



 The Virgin Mary, the mother of Jesus, is often depicted as a white woman with subtle and soft features despite her Israeli heritage. Mary is seen as the pinnacle of biblical womanhood.
Shift A, right B, Nintendo 63

This could be a part of the famous Kunami Code (Up, Up, Down, Down, Left, Right, Left, Right, B, A) that was first used in 1986. Itz’s used to enable cheat codes in Kunami Games and often used as an easter egg in other games. However, the lines seem to state that the mysterious girl does them the other way around (shift A right B instead of Right B, Shift A). This could mean that instead of expanding the singer’s horizon (enable cheat codes), she does the exact opposite so the singer only concentrates on her now. Two lines after she states: The game she’s been changing.
And she spins me around like a marionette

This is where the theme of predetermined destiny in this song starts, because a marionette is a puppet with its limbs controlled by strings (like the spiders webs in the next line.) Here, though, being spun like a marionette sounds romantic, like dancing- refer to the comment about worshipping the vague idea of a lover.
https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/marionette

My web is still spinning
 You can’t see it yet

“my web is still spinning/you can’t see it yet” has 3 parts: the first being the phrase “web of fate” and the second is the connection to the lyric “And she spins me around like a marionette”, with ‘spins’ being the word for a spider producing webs. The third is the Fates in Greek mythology, who spin the threads of human destiny. https://www.britannica.com/topic/Fate-Greek-and-Roman-mythology
The honeycomb holding you

Like Honeycomb holding the bees in the fold"
- Excript from jo, by  Haley Heynderickx

Honeycomb, as referenced in the Song “Jo”, seems refers to a safe place built by protectors/caregivers; a feeling of safety.

description.plain:
I was living in a house with six women at the time and attempting to pursue music as more than a bedroom act. In this, I was struggling to find confidence and purpose in it. Writing “Worth It” was a cathartic release at the time, just allowing myself to take up space and make as much noise as I could in our basement without driving my roommates too crazy. After several weeks, this song got carved out. It has been through a lot and it means something new to me each time I hear it.
- Haley Heynderickx
